# Comments in New Code

When adding **new** files, components, functions, or non-trivial logic blocks, include brief comments that explain **why** the code exists and what it does.

## What to comment

- **New files**: A short header comment describing the feature or module's role.
- **New exports** (components, hooks, classes, utilities): A one-line doc comment on purpose and when to use it.
- **Non-obvious logic**: Comments for placement algorithms, shortcuts, state resets, side effects, or integration points with external APIs.

## What to skip

- Do not narrate obvious code (`// increment i`).
- Do not comment unchanged existing code unless you are modifying it.
- Prefer self-explanatory names; use comments where intent is not clear from the code alone.

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — no context on a new feature module
export const BrainstormMode = () => {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);
  // ...
};

// ✅ GOOD — new component explains its purpose
/** Rapid sticky-note capture overlay toggled by Cmd/Ctrl+Shift+B. */
export const BrainstormMode = () => {
  // ...
};

// ✅ GOOD — non-obvious placement logic
// Cascade stickies diagonally from viewport center; wrap after 8 to stay on screen.
const col = dropIndex % CASCADE_WRAP;
```

Keep comments concise (1–2 lines). Update or remove comments when behavior changes.
